    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>Slab avalanches and moist loose snow avalanches are the main danger.</highlights>
      <comment>The fresh snow and the wind slabs can be released easily, or, in isolated cases naturally and generally at intermediate and high altitudes. Mostly the avalanches are medium-sized and can be released even by a single winter sport participant. &lt;br/> As a consequence of warming and solar radiation, the natural activity of moist and wet avalanches will gradually increase. This applies in particular on steep slopes especially at low and intermediate altitudes. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Ski touring and other off-piste activities, including snowshoe hiking, call for experience in the assessment of avalanche danger and careful route selection.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>Up to 60 cm of snow, and even more in some localities, has fallen since Saturday. Over a wide area new snow is lying on a hard crust. &lt;br/> The new snow is bonding only slowly with the old snowpack in particular on shady slopes. The covering of new snow is soft and its surface has a crust that is not capable of bearing a load. &lt;br/> The moderate wind has transported the new snow. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Intermediate and high altitudes: Individual weak layers exist in the old snowpack especially on shady slopes.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
